Using a VariantExperiment data object to manage COVID19 data

Jerome Ambroise, Laurent Gatto, Julie Hurel, Bertrand Bearzatto, Jean-Luc Gala

April 01, 2021,19:02

In this document we illustrate the advantages of using the VariantExperiment Bioconductor package for handling SARS-CoV-2 genomic data and associated metadata. For more details, we invite you to read the associated publication (‘On the many advantages of using the VariantExperiment Bioconductor package for storing, exchanging and analyzing SARS-CoV-2 genomic data and associated metadata’ available on bioRxiv.org).

1 Load package

library(VariantExperiment)

2 Data loading

The RangedSummarizedExperiment object was created with the VariantExperiment package for handling SARS-COV2 genomic data and associated ‘dummy’ (in the present study) metadata.

sarscov2_ve <- readRDS('sarscov2_ve.rds')

3 Data management

The object contains 38 variants sequenced in 10 different samples.

sarscov2_ve

It now becomes easy to produce a graphical overview of the genotypes of the read depth of a dataset by plotting the respective assay heatmap.

pheatmap::pheatmap(assay(sarscov2_ve, "genotype"))

Heatmap of the virus genotypes. 

pheatmap::pheatmap(assay(sarscov2_ve, "DP"))

Heatmap of the sequencing read depth illustrating how some samples have systematic low read depth (blue).

4 Subsetting

Here we illustrate how to subset the object. For the demonstration we select only data:

  • from patient with obesity (Obesity = yes)
  • mutation with a start position < 5000
sel_start <- start(SummarizedExperiment::rowRanges(sarscov2_ve)) < 5000
sel_obesity <- sarscov2_ve$Obesity == 'yes'

ve2 <- sarscov2_ve[sel_start, sel_obesity]
ve2
## class: VariantExperiment 
## dim: 6 2 
## metadata(0):
## assays(2): genotype DP
## rownames(6): MN908947.3:241_C/T MN908947.3:313_C/T ...
##   MN908947.3:3036_TCT/TTT MN908947.3:3176_C/T
## rowData names(7): paramRangeID REF ... VOC2 VOC1
## colnames(2): ax1233122 ax1233125
## colData names(19): Sample.ID Date ... has_VOC2 has_VOC1

As shown here the selection is performed in one operation for both the rowData, colData and assay(s). This property therefore ensures to keep a perfect synchronization of genomic data with metadata.

We can also make use the the VOC/VOI definition in the rowData slot to extract and focus on the set of mutated loci of each variant:

voc1 <- sarscov2_ve[rowData(sarscov2_ve)$VOC1, ]
assay(voc1, "genotype")
## <2 x 10 x 1> array of class DelayedArray and type "integer":

Below, we use the sample-level metadata to extract the samples that have been annotated as having been infected by certain variants of concern:

has_VOC1 <- sarscov2_ve[, sarscov2_ve$has_VOC1]
assay(has_VOC1, "genotype")
## <38 x 3 x 1> array of class DelayedArray and type "integer":
## ,,1
##                                 ax1233128 ax1233121 ax1233125
##              MN908947.3:241_C/T         1         0         0
##              MN908947.3:313_C/T         1         0         0
##                             ...         .         .         .
##          MN908947.3:28882_GG/AC         1         0         0
## MN908947.3:29377_TAAAAAG/TAAAAG         0         0         0
has_VOC2 <- sarscov2_ve[, sarscov2_ve$has_VOC2]
assay(has_VOC2, "genotype")
## <38 x 3 x 1> array of class DelayedArray and type "integer":
## ,,1
##                                 ax1233129 ax1233122 ax1233124
##              MN908947.3:241_C/T         0         0         0
##              MN908947.3:313_C/T         0         0         0
##                             ...         .         .         .
##          MN908947.3:28882_GG/AC         1         0         0
## MN908947.3:29377_TAAAAAG/TAAAAG         1         1         1

Both subsetting can of course be applied simultaneously to extract the variants of concern loci in the patients that have been infected by that particular VOC:

is_voc1 <- sarscov2_ve[rowData(sarscov2_ve)$VOC1, sarscov2_ve$has_VOC1]
assay(is_voc1, "genotype")
## <2 x 3 x 1> array of class DelayedArray and type "integer":
## ,,1
##                                  sample.id
## variant.id                        ax1233128 ax1233121 ax1233125
##   MN908947.3:5224_TAAAAAG/TAAAAG          1         1         1
##   MN908947.3:22487_GAAAAAG/GAAAAG         1         1         1
is_voc2 <- sarscov2_ve[rowData(sarscov2_ve)$VOC2, sarscov2_ve$has_VOC2]
assay(is_voc2, "genotype")
## <1 x 3 x 1> array of class DelayedArray and type "integer":

##       sample.id

5.3 Sample annotations/metadata (aka colData)

col_data <- DataFrame(read.csv('coldata.csv'))
rownames(col_data) <- col_data$Sample.ID
col_data <- col_data[match(colnames(sarscov2_ve), col_data$SRA.ID), ]
stopifnot(identical(colnames(sarscov2_ve), col_data$SRA.ID))
SummarizedExperiment::colData(sarscov2_ve) <- col_data

5.4 Feature annotations/medata (aka rowData)

vcffile.fb <- readVcf('variant.q20.vcf')
rowRanges(sarscov2_ve) <- SummarizedExperiment::rowRanges(vcffile.fb)

5.5 Annotation of variants of interest/concern

As an example, we define two variants of concern, VOC1 and VOC2:

  • VOC1 is defined by 2 loci, namely "MN908947.3:5224_TAAAAAG/TAAAAG" and "MN908947.3:22487_GAAAAAG/GAAAAG"
  • VOC2 is defined by "MN908947.3:29377_TAAAAAG/TAAAAG"

These VOCs are defined as logical columns in the rowData slot, with matching loci set to TRUE.

rowData(sarscov2_ve)$VOC1 <- rowData(sarscov2_ve)$VOC2 <- FALSE
rowData(sarscov2_ve)$VOC1[c(7, 26)] <- TRUE
rowData(sarscov2_ve)$VOC2[38] <- TRUE

Below, we manually define which samples have been infected by specific variants of concern.

sarscov2_ve$has_VOC1 <- sarscov2_ve$has_VOC2 <- FALSE
sarscov2_ve$has_VOC1[c(2, 6, 9)] <- TRUE
sarscov2_ve$has_VOC2[c(3, 5, 8)] <- TRUE

5.6 Serialisation of the object

saveRDS(sarscov2_ve, 'sarscov2_ve.rds')
